column39: Conduct that is Negligent Because it was Instrumental for the Defendant's Negligence
column41: Potentially other sections of the Restatement relevant
column44: Comment
sole issue on appeal is contributory negligence (which was a complete bar at this time)
Touches on relevant negligence issues but deals primarily with propriety of summary judgement
Summary judgement case concerning negligence of utility company for its placement of electricity line
summary judgement dealing mostly with sufficiency of facts forming basis for summary judgement; discusses relevance of witness testimony evidence and thus of marginal relevance

Concerns whether a jury could have find in favour of one defendant and not another given identical factual situation but different scope of liability. Marginal because discussion of negligence is brief, but usefully discusses whether non-use of certain school laboratory equipment can be negligent (it can).

yes: whether failure to order abdominal tests and consequently to diagnose abdominal rupture was breach of physician duty (summary judgement reversed on this basis); special concurrence on ancillary issue of which locality rule (for evaluating standard of care) should be followed.
deals with whether defendant vehicle passenger can be liable to plaintiff for collision because defendant assisted in looking for oncoming vehicles; 'matter of first impression in NM'.

concerns whether defendant blood bank breached duty of care for providing hepatitis-infected blood to recipient plaintiff. No breach because no way to test for infection in blood and all regulations complied with. NOTE: contains alternating majority opinion—majority opinion on negligence delivered by different composition of court to majority opinion on strict liability (which I did not tag).

Marginal because case deals with whether plaintiff was contributorily negligent for failure to act with care required of a reasonable person in the circumstances; that is, defendant's duty and breach has been established, and the case turns on whether the plaintiff (a) had a duty; and (b) acted in accordance with it. NOTE: emergency apparent on facts, but not discussed in this judgement since it was concerned with whether a duty existed, not whether the plaintiff had acted in an emergency.

Marginal because case concerns whether evidence is sufficiently substantial to support finding of negligence by trial court, as opposed to whether conduct was negligent more directly (that is, the judgement of the trial court was affirmed, so we know the facts detail negligence, but that's inferred from the explicit judgement which is simply that the evidence is not so insubstantial as to warrant being overturned).

Case is slightly messy in that repeated reference is made to disputed testimony, but ultimately negligence is apparent where there is a failure to properly light the side of the road behind a disabled car.
Summary judgement case holding that defendant store owner has no duty to warn customers of dangers that would be obvious to those exercising ordinary care.

Potentially marginal because I have doubts that this is still good law (that felons can be apprehended with force that risks their death whenever they try to escape if that's the only way to stop them); refers to section 131 of the original Restatement of Torts on the use of force in this way.

Marginal because case effectively simply states duty of building owner to business invitee—and the fact that that duty does not change whether or not a warning has been given prior to entry to the premises—but does not establish that facts of the case indicate negligence

Concerns duty of driver to pedestrians, and discusses statutory duty of pedestrians to give way which does not militate against inability of children to be found guilty of contributory negligence. Marginal because relevant issues are only briefly discussed.

summary judgement case; whether a particular medical practice suggested by one medical expert can establish an issue of fact about whether use of a different medical practice was negligent. The practice was not in general use and failure to perform it was not negligent.

summary judgement case: whether using foot to dislodge cotton stripper machinery blockage was contributorily negligent (it was), and whether the fact that that conduct was common practice rendered the conduct reasonable (it didn't)
Marginal because case deals only by extension and briefly with issues of negligence
Case concerning whether evidence permitted inference that other explanations than the defendant's conduct were the cause of a driving accident
Whether it was negligent to jump into a car and drive away with the plaintiff sitting in the front seat (and who subsequently jumped out of the car in fear, injuring herself)

Case concerns whether a plaintiff with no sense of smell could be contributorily negligent for lighting a match at a petrol station even though she could not smell petrol fumes (she could be found to be negligent because it was not required that she voluntarily expose herself to the risk; she may have fallen below the required standard of care even if she could not smell petrol fumes).

Case concerns whether cutting too deeply during spinal surgery was malpractice (it was shown that incidents such as this occurred even in surgery carried out with due care, so the surgeon defendant had not been negligent).

Case concerns whether defendant was negligent in discharging a firearm accidentally which accident caused the plaintiff's death (the defendant was found by the jury not to have been negligent because he was a child and the plaintiff had engaged in contributory negligence)

whether a bus driver is negligent for stopping abruptly and opening the bus door at the same time (they are), and whether a passenger assumes the risk of injury inherent in standing up before the bus has stopped (they assume only ordinary risk). Potentially marginal because judgement deals primarily with sufficiency of evidence rather than elements of negligence.

marginal because most discussion in the judgement concerns propriety of jury instruction on unavoidable accident, not discussion of whether acts constitute negligence, but useful because there is discussion of whether defendant, acting in a short period of time, had the last clear chance of avoiding injury

summary judgement case  concerncing scope of duty owed by business occupier to public; sets a precedent, overturns older cases dealing with scope of duty to plaintiffs not exercising reasonable care; marginal in relation to applicability of failure to warn/adoption of further precautions, because the court discusses adequacy of precautions taken, but merely concludes that such an issue should have been put to the jury.

Summary judgement case concerning statutory duty of ski operator; discusses duty on part of plaintiff, and statutory duty to warn plaintiff of harm, but does not resolve these issues—just determines that they constitute issues of material fact.
summary judgement case on scope of liability of fair operators for injuries off their premises
Summary judgement case concerning material facts pertaining to adequacy of equipment provided to employee and scope of duty of employer to protect against obvious risks
Summary judgement case concerning whether duty owed by employer police department to take reasonable care in hiring police officers.

Case concerning whether duty of care owed to parents of deceased victim for loss of financial and emotional support; MARGINAL because limited application of law to facts, narrow consideration of existence of duty in well-established area of law, and limited relationship between factual scenario in which harm occurred and existence/breach of duty by tortfeasor (that is, discussion concerned scope of duty to parents, not related to facts of injury to son)

Summary judgement case concerning death arising from unsafe riding of pickup truck: whether defendant should have known passengers riding unsafely; and whether baseball should reasonably have foreseen likelihood of disobedience giving rise to injury; MARGINAL because of whether facts do or do not amount to negligence (discussion merely concerns whether those facts are in issue, so of limited relevance to determination of actual negligence).
Summary judgement case concerning scope of duty of proprietor of land to passersby when land used for a concert
MARGINAL summary judgement case concerning whether defendant made prima facie showing of absence of dispute over material facts; marginal because minimal discussion of relevant elements of negligence

Whether duty owed to wife of defendant's contractor for completing work that benefits defendant to take statutorily-imposed precautions for preventing injury from building work. MARGINAL because discussion primarily concerns propriety of summary judgement, not actual occurrence of negligence

whether defendant proprietor has duty to remove snow from private parking lot during snowstorm. Case of first impression in dealing with duty of private parties to clean ice and snow from private property
Whether the defendant was negligent in failing to clean its store regularly such that gum was left on the floor causing the plaintiff's injuries

Potentially marginal because case deals primarily with propriety of summary judgement and quotes extensively from other cases in determining application of law to facts (rather than applying law to facts directly), with little discussion of facts of the case.

Potentially marginal because majority of judgement deals with whether evidence was sufficient to ground trial court's denial of motion for directed verdict, and discussion of propriety of requested jury instructions, rather than deciding whether or not negligence had occurred

Summary judgement case. Whether plaintiff contributorily negligent for standing between two cars on the side of the road at night, and whether a parent can sue an adult child despite the fact that the parent provides financial and emotional support and they live together (they can). POTENTIALLY MARGINAL because case merely concludes that the cirucmstances give rise to issues of fact that should have been put to the jury.

abolition of assumption of risk doctrine, dealing with whether employee was contributorily negligent for working in ditch with risk of injury. Potentially marginal because discussion of actual negligence is rpactically non-existent; rather, case deals with whether summary judgement should have beeng granted.

Whether defendant parking lot operator had duty to warn, remove the danger, or expect harm to arise from ice on the parking lot, and whether the plaintiff assumed the risk or could have been contributorily negligent (summary judgement). Potentially marginal because summary judgement and discussion of whether acts constituted negligence is entirely absent.
establishes applicability of strict liability in tort to those who rent products such as cars (which duty previously applied only to manufacturers in product liability cases)

summary judgement case. Whether plaintiff employee was contributorily negligent in failing to examine electric cables before attempting to remove them from an electric pole (this is a matter for the jury), and whether defendant property owner and defendant electrical companies owed the plaintiff, an employee of an independent contractor, a duty of care (they did).
summary judgement case: whether duty of doctor to warn private nurse plaintiff of dangerous patient (no duty when doctor could not have known of dangerousness).

marginal because court, in deciding that a motion for a directed verdict was rightly rejected, deals only briefly and inconclusively with relevant issue of whether plaintiff was contributorily negligent.

Marginal only because discussion focuses on propriety of jury instructions about sudden emergency and entitlement of defendant to rely on lawful driving of other drivers (though discussion is relevant)
Potentially marginal (of limited utility) only because fact and application of law discussion is very brief.
Marginal: confusingly written, and with reference to facts and instructions that are not stated, poor account of facts overall, and only limited, tangential discussion of relevant issues.

Marginal because only limited discussion of facts and discussion predominantly concerns matters of law (when contractor should be liable for work done and accepted), and does not resolve facts, or specify under what circumstances a contractor is NOT liable. Clarifies the law on whether a contractor's negligence can be superseded by the party accepting their work.
Overturns 0516
Potentially marginal because case primarily concerns whether one defendant should be indemnified by another, but relevant issues are substantially discussed.
Establishes applicability of amended § 343 of Restatement (duty given dangerous conditions known to possessor of land)
Potentially marginal because case disposed partially on grounds of exceptions to statutory immunity, but makes relevant comments about duties of landowners for dangers not on their property.
Relies heavily on Restatement § 318 duty to protect plaintiff from dangers arising on defendant's land brought about or caused by third parties

marginal because case deals primarily with whether expert is qualified to establish the medical standard of care in a locality in which he does not practice (he is so qualified); but the case establishes that a failure to address abdominal bleeding is below the standard of care in these circumstances, so is still relevant.
Potentially marginal because case deals primarily with propriety of summary judgement, but considers factual issues which go to negligence of defendant glass manufacturer.

potentially marginal because case deals primarily with whether expert testimony was necessary to establish the standard of care; but also establishes that a doctor's failure to follow a specialist's advice on blood transfusions may amount to a breach of the standard of care.

potentially marginal because case predominantly discusses whether expert testimony was required to establish the standard of care, but does also establish that it was not negligent to leave a canula tip inside the patient's knee.

Extremely marginal because restatement of facts merely describes the occurrence of a vehicle collision in which the plaintiff was injured, and conclusion is expressed in terms of whether the evidence supports the jury's verdict; but case indicates that defendant can be negligent in the circumstances of a collision for failing to keep a proper lookout when defendant attests that she was not paying attention.

Marginal because case deals primarily with whether evidence established that defendant's act in dispensing incorrect medication was the proximate cause of PTSD; but court found that jury's finding of negligence was based on substantial evidence, and the facts were sufficiently stated to be useful.

Potentially marginal because case does not decisively state whether actions of defendant were negligent, just that they may have been (jury found in defendant's favour but after receiving sudden emergency instruction even though defendant may have contributed to the emergency). Makes new law: abolishes sudden emergency jury instruction.
potentially marginal: confusing fact recount and judgement which relates to multiple defendants in the same primary fact situation but accused of negligence for different alleged medical failures.
Potentially marginal only because discussion of facts is extremely brief.
Potentially marginal because negligence is admitted by the defendant (and the appeal relates to proximate cause); still useful since facts are detailed.
Marginal because discussion of negligence of defendants is, at best, implicit in finding that jury instructions were proper (jury found negligence).
Marginal because facts are convoluted and both facts and judgement relate only in part to issues of negligence

marginal because factual scenario is contested (equal testimony in both directions) and primary issue is propriety of jury instructions. However, clearly establishes that failure to recommend hospitalisation to patient with symptoms of heart attack is negligent.

Potentially marginal because issue is resolved in terms of causation (that manufacturer could not have foreseen significant alteration to machine causing injury), but case is indicative because the clear but implicit statement of the court is that there is no duty in negligence on part of the manufacturer to guard against injury arising from significant alteration to a manufactured machine.

Court deals with two defendants where one is held to be liable and the other not liable. Nevertheless, facts relate primarily to failure to inspect and replace a decaying power pole, and thus primarily point to negligence notwithstanding the outcome in respect of second, not-liable defendant.

A wife operation a vehicle in such a way that carbon monoxide travelled into the bedroom where her husband was sleeping, causing his death. One of the issues the court considered was whether there was sufficient evidence of the wife’s negligence.

Only one of the questions the court considered was whether the fact that the plaintiff had three prior abortions, and may not have told one of the defendants this prior to labour, was a relevant fact (i.e., whether it had the tendency to show that the plaintiff breached a duty of exercising ordinary care for her safety).
No real discussion of the elements of the tort of negligence. Nevertheless, the facts with the decision are indicative of the court's finding on negligence.

About police officers' immunity under the Tort Claims Act following their failure to take a drunk driver off the road. Briefly discusses whether the police could be said to have been guilty of violation of statutory duty.

Borderline. Bar owner failed to protect its patrons from the foreseeable violent acts of a third party. The question was whether the bar owner’s liability could be reduced based on the intentional acts of a third party.  The case does, however, indicate that the court considered the bar's conduct as negligent

There is no facts section in this case; the decision just refers to an earlier Supreme Court decision. However, I have left it in because there are a few mentions of the facts which give a high-level picture of what happened.

Plaintiff brought a claim against the wrongful death of her husband in connection with a plane crash. Plaintiff sued in negligence and strict liability, claiming that the absence of shoulder harnesses caused the death of her husband. Most of the judgment concerns whether a design-defect claim may be brought in both negligence and strict liability, though the court briefly discusses whether there was evidence of negligence.

Occupier's liability. Plaintiff was injured when she fell on a sidewalk leading to a store in a shopping centre. The sidewalk was obviously in disrepair. The question was whether the defendants were obligated to protect plaintiff against an open and obvious danger. The court held yes, but that only the owner of the shopping centre had this duty, not the store.

Plaintiffs wanted to alter a car’s fuel system so that it could run on liquid propane in addition to gasoline. It took the car to the defendants. The defendants negligently serviced the car. Propane leaked from a valve and ignited, causing a fire and injuring plaintiffs, who were in the car. The plaintiffs sued for negligence and failure to warn. The relevant part of the case that mentions defendant's negligence is actually about the instructions given to the jury. Nevertheless, the court affirmed the trial court's judgment that the defendant was negligent.

Marked as "marginal" because most of the discussion was about whether the trial court was right to accept certain evidence. The appeal court's judgments on these matters is therefore very weak (e.g. 'the trial court was right to accept this evidence, as it could give rise to an inference of [X]'...). Summary: Driver crashed into a tree, killing its passengers and injuring himself. There were no eye-witnesses. The jury apportioned liability among the driver, passengers, Rio Arriba County and New Mexico State Highway Department. The court considered evidence relating to the passengers’ intoxication, overcrowding in the car, whether the driver and passengers faced an ‘emergency’ and the statutory liability of the New Mexico State Highway Department.

Two detainees escaped from prison and killed the deceased. Plaintiff for the deceased brought several claims against various government officials. The court considered whether the state police had a duty to the deceased and whether they breached this. A small part of the decision discusses the case against the state police, which obviously fell outside the statute immunity.

Only relevant part of the judgment concerns whether a violation of the New Mexico Occupational Health and Safety Act can form the basis of a claim for statutory negligence per se. The rest of the case concerns workplace liability under the special rules of the Restatement, including issues of vicarious liability.

Large portion of the case discusses the development of the seatbelt defense in New Mexico. In addition, most of the arguments brought by the defendant were very specific to the evidence presented in the earlier trial, and so there is little substance in this case that will help the model.
About a doctor who prescribes drugs to patient, who then gets into a car and injures a third party. About the doctor's duty to the third party.
States that a cause of action exists, but there is no real application of the law to the facts.
Vicarious liability also raised, but marginally (discussion was more about whether the employee was negligent)

Concerns a case by a defendant against other defendants. Borderline because the woording of the case may confuse the model. A plaintiff was injured after grabbing a guy wire which had become accidentally discharged. The Cooperative, one of the defendants, had that power line constructed on the land of Castonguay. The Cooperative settled its claim with the plaintiff, then sought recovery from the other defendants. In one of its claims, the Cooperative claimed that Castonguay, who owned the property on which the line was constructed, breached his duty to the plaintiff. The trail court entered summary judgment to Castonguay. The appeal court agreed and affirmed the trial court’s judgment.
Concerns the duty of care owed by an owner to an invitee or a licensee. The court amended the current law to say that the duty of care in these cases is the same duty.

Plaintiff’s father was run over and killed by a backing tractor-trailer truck. The truck had no audible reverse signal alarm installed. Plaintiff sued both the manufacturer and seller of the tractor and trailer, as well as the record owner of the tractor-trailer. He claimed under strict liability and negligence theory. The trial court gave summary judgment in favour of the defendants, and the appellate court reversed. On the court's reasoning, the negligence case seemed to hinge on the strict liability case.

Mainly sovereign immunity case, but the court made a single sentence that tehre is a material question of fact relating to the defendants' negligence. Plaintiff worked near an area where the defendants did firemen training drills, which included burning vehicles. The plaintiff was injured by the fumes from the burning so sued for negligence. The trial court granted summary judgment on the basis of the defendants’ sovereign immunity. The appellate court reversed.

Case concerns whether a tavernkeeper who has served alcohol to someone who is intoxicated owes a duty to a third party who is subsequently injured by the intoxicated person. The Supreme Court changed the common law and held that the tavernkeeper has such a duty under common law negligence.

Case concerns whether there should be a ‘fireman’s rule’ in New Mexico. Namely, whether an owner/occupier owes a duty of care to a fireman that arrives at their property to help to fight a fire. The court held that there should be a ‘fireman’s rule’ in New Mexico.
Also touches uppon landlord's duty to tenants
Discusses rules on occupier's liability

Plaintiff (employee of the defendant) tripped and fell over a painter’s drop cloth as she was leaving work. Court considered whether the defendant (owner of the commercial building) could be held vicariously liable for the negligence of the independent contractor in leaving the cloth on the floor. The court held that it could. The case also raised issues of contributory negligence and negligence of the contractor.

Plaintiff was injured while working on a farm. The trial court ruled in favour of the defendants and the plaintiff appealed. The appellate court affirmed the judgment. Court does not comment on any specific facts, so it is not entirely helpful.

Plaintiff was injured when a jar fell on her ankle and she went to a doctor. Her ankle did not respond to the first two treatments, and later the doctor found a piece of glass still in her ankle. Plaintiff sued, but did not present any medical testimony, so the trial court directed a verdict for the doctor. Plaintiff appealed and the appellate court affirmed. Borderline, because the court really only discussed the requirement for medical testimony.

Marginal because the court did not cite any facts, but only the testimony of a medical expert (on which it relied for the ruling). Plaintiff alleged that decedent received negligent treatment at a hospital and subsequently died. Plaintiff relied on testimony from a medical expert. The trial court excluded the testimony, and subsequently ordered summary judgment in favour of the defendant. The appellate court held that the testimony should not have been excluded, and that, based on the testimony, there is a genuine issue of material fact for the jury to determine.

Borderline because it does not identify any specific evidence on which it based its conclusion. Plaintiff sued defendant, alleging malpractice. Specifically, plaintiff claimed that defendant doctor performed unnecessary surgery, which exacerbated her pain and problems, and because defendant did not consult with a colorectal surgeon before he performed the surgery. The jury found for the defendant. The appellate court confirmed.

Very marginal case. Plaintiffs’ barge crashed into defendants’ ski boat. One of the issues was whether the trial court abused its discretion in refusing to admit evidence that the defendants were intoxicated. The trial court stated the evidence regarding alcohol was not admissible unless there was some evidence that the driver of the ski boat was in fact intoxicated, and the trial court concluded there was no such evidence. The appellate court claimed that the trial court did not abuse its discretion in this regard.

Borderline case. Decedent was an ironworker who fell to his death when a defective eye loop gave way on the end of a cable supporting a swinging scaffold on which Mr. Elliott stood. Plaintiff sued a number of entities. The trial court granted summary judgment in relation to one of the entities, W. E. Clark & Sons, Inc (Clark) and the plaintiff appealed. The appellate court reversed. Borderline because the issue is more about who was negligent than whether negligence existed.
Creates dramshop liability (a cause of action against a vendor of liquor who knowingly sells alcohol to a minor.)

Borderline. No evidence properly examined. Plaintiffs were injured while using a scissor lift to install pipe at defendant Nucor’s facility. A default judgment was entered in favour of plaintiffs. Defendant motioned to set aside the default judgment on the basis that the complaint failed to state facts upon which relief can be granted. The trial court denied the motion, and the appellate court affirmed.
Concerns landlord duties to tenants, but also instructive about negligence in general.

Some of the case discusses duty of warn in strict (product) liability and in premises liability (i.e. landlord's duty to guest)  but in a way that is probably instructive for negligence claims as well.

Mostly concerns procedural issues, but seems to point to contributory negligence. Defendant was a pharmacy. It allegedly misfilled decedent’s prescription, causing decedent to ingest stronger prescription medications than he believed. Decedent died following a massive brain bleed caused by the wrong prescription tablets. Plaintiffs brought an action against defendants. A jury returned a verdict in favour of plaintiff and defendant appealed. One of the issues raised was whether the decedent’s wife (one of the plaintiffs) was guilty of contributory negligence. The case was remanded on several grounds

Borderline case. Plaintiff made a claim for compensation under the Crime Victims Compensation Act after her daughter was killed in an automobile accident involving a drunken driver on December 6, 1993. The question for the court was whether the award should be reduced in light of the plaintiff’s daughter’s contributory negligence in choosing to ride with a person she knew to be drinking and who could be impaired. The award was reduced.

Borderline because considers wilful and wanton conduct as opposed to negligence. Plaintiff tripped on a sidewalk and sued the park district for wilful and wanton conduct. The trial court granted summary judgment to the defendant, holding that its actions did not amount to wilful and wanton conduct. The appellate court confirmed.

Marginal case because the case was rejected for failure to provide expert evidence as to standard of care. However, the court noted that, based on the evidence, the State was negligent in not following the doctor’s orders to provide the plaintiff with a lower bunk.
About landowner's duty (in an employment context)
Marginal because the facts section is very sparse

Main application of law to facts concerns the standard of care which should apply and the trial court's error in applying the wrong standard of care.  Here, the appellate court heard that the appropriate standard of care was ordinary negligence (not professional), but this judgment was considered to be favourable to plaintiff.

Involves a landowner's liability and the rule established in Kahn v James Burton that a possessor of land is liable for injuries sustained by children when the injury is caused by a dangerous condition on the property and the owner knew or should have known that young people habitually frequent the area

Plaintiff underwent heart surgery. A few weeks later, while recovering, plaintiff swallowed a toothpick and had surgery to remove this. During plaintiff’s postoperative recovery, plaintiff received five enemas. He subsequently had a heart attack, which he claimed resulted from the stress caused by the multiple anemas. The trial court barred the plaintiff’s expert’s testimony and granted summary judgment in favour of defendant. The appellate court reversed the decision to bar plaintiff’s expert’s testimony, and held that given the conflicting expert testimony, summary judgment was inappropriate.
